# .trivyignore — Trivy CVE allowlist for the M4.8 CI quality gate.
#
# Two-pass scan model in CI:
#   1. SARIF report at CRITICAL+HIGH severity, non-blocking, uploaded to
#      GitHub Security tab. This file silences known-acceptable findings
#      from the SARIF view to keep the inbox actionable.
#   2. Blocking gate at CRITICAL severity. This file is honored here too —
#      adding a CVE here suppresses the build failure as well as the SARIF
#      report.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Triage workflow:
#   1. CVE shows up in the Security tab. Click through to the advisory.
#   2. Decide: is the vulnerable code path actually reachable from MyProperty?
#      - Transitive dep we don't use directly → low risk; allowlist with date.
#      - Direct dep with no fix yet → allowlist with date; bump when patched.
#      - Direct dep with a fix → bump the dep instead of allowlisting.
#   3. Add an entry below in the form:
#        CVE-YYYY-NNNNN exp:YYYY-MM-DD  # short rationale
#      The `exp:` annotation is read by humans, not Trivy. Review every entry
#      monthly and re-evaluate when its `exp:` date passes.
#
# Severity-level tuning:
#   - CRITICAL is the blocking gate. Allowlist a CVE here only with strong
#     justification (e.g. confirmed not reachable, upstream advisory marks
#     it as not-affected for the runtime).
#   - HIGH appears in the SARIF report only. Allowlisting still cleans up
#     the inbox but does not gate the build.
#
# References:
#   - https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/
#   - docs/operations/security-hardening.md  (full Trivy section)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Initial baseline (M4.8 close): empty allowlist. Anything that surfaces in
# the first post-merge scan goes here with a triage decision attached, or
# gets fixed at the source.

# libssl3 OpenSSL bundle (CVE-2026-31789 + 4 HIGH siblings) — frontend image only
# (distroless nodejs runtime). Debian shipped fixed libssl3 (3.0.19/3.0.20-1~deb12u2,
# 2026-06-09), but gcr.io/distroless has NOT rebuilt its nodejs images against the
# patched packages yet — verified by direct Trivy scan on 2026-06-12: the current
# nodejs22 AND nodejs24 :nonroot digests both still ship libssl3 3.0.18-1~deb12u2.
# Practical exposure is negligible while we wait:
#   - Node bundles its own statically-linked OpenSSL (process.versions.openssl =
#     3.5.x); the only process in the container never loads the flagged libssl3.
#   - CVE-2026-31789 is 32-bit-only and needs a >1 GB certificate per Debian's
#     triage; our images are amd64/arm64.
# Remove this block AND re-pin the runtime to a rebuilt nodejs24 digest as soon as
# distroless ships the patched libssl3 (daily Dependabot docker checks will surface
# the rebuild as a digest-bump PR). See image-hardening-plan.md PR-2.
CVE-2026-31789 exp:2026-07-01  # libssl3; CRITICAL per Trivy, not applicable per Debian triage; node uses bundled OpenSSL
CVE-2026-28387 exp:2026-07-01  # libssl3 OpenSSL DANE UAF, HIGH (SARIF inbox cleanup)
CVE-2026-28388 exp:2026-07-01  # libssl3 OpenSSL NULL deref in delta, HIGH
CVE-2026-28389 exp:2026-07-01  # libssl3 OpenSSL CMS DoS, HIGH
CVE-2026-28390 exp:2026-07-01  # libssl3 OpenSSL NULL deref in CMS, HIGH
